{"conflict_recognized": 0, "processed_response": "A 2-stroke motor and a 4-stroke motor differ primarily in their operation cycles. A 2-stroke engine completes a power cycle in two strokes of the piston (one revolution of the crankshaft). This means that it fires once every revolution, leading to higher power output for its size. In contrast, a 4-stroke engine completes a power cycle in four strokes (two revolutions of the crankshaft), firing once every two revolutions.

